<assessment id="u4_m2_testprop7_tutor3">
    <title>Tutor</title>
    <page>
        
        <question id="q1">
            <body>
                <p>The p-value is the probability of observing a sample proportion that is
                        <input_ref input="G"/> </p> <p>standard deviations or more <input_ref input="H"/>
                        p<sub>0</sub> = <input_ref input="I"/>,</p> <p>assuming that the true population
                    proportion is <input_ref input="J"/>.</p>
            </body>
            <numeric id="G" size="small"/>
            <fill_in_the_blank id="H">
                <choice value="one">above</choice>
                <choice value="two">below</choice>
                <choice value="three">away from</choice>
            </fill_in_the_blank>
            <numeric id="I" size="small"/>
            <numeric id="J" size="small"/>
            <part>
                <response input="G" match="1.21" score="1">
                    <feedback>Correct. The z-value tells us the number of standard deviations p-hat is from p<sub>0</sub>.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response input="G" match="-1.21">
                    <feedback>Not quite right. You are right that the z-value is −1.21. That means the sample
                        proportion is 1.21 standard deviations below p<sub>0</sub>.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response input="G" match="*">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. The z-value is the number of standard
                        deviations p-hat is from p<sub>0</sub>.</feedback>
                </response>
                <hint>The z-value is the number of standard
                    deviations p-hat is from p<sub>0</sub>.</hint>
                <hint>The z-value is −1.21, so the sample
                    proportion is 1.21 standard deviations below p<sub>0</sub>.</hint>
            </part>
            <part>
                <response input="H" match="one">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. Look at H<sub>a</sub>.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response input="H" match="two" score="1">
                    <feedback>Correct. The "&lt;" in H<sub>a</sub> tells us to look at sample
                        proportions below the observed p-hat from the data.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response input="H" match="three">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. Look at H<sub>a</sub>.</feedback>
                </response>
                <hint>The "&lt;" in H<sub>a</sub> tells us to look at sample
                    proportions below the observed p-hat from the data.</hint>
            </part>
            <part>
                <response input="I" match="0.45" score="1">
                    <feedback>Correct. The null hypothesis states the value of p<sub>0</sub>.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response input="I" match="*">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. What is the null hypothesis?</feedback>
                </response>
                <hint>Look at the null hypothesis.</hint>
                <hint>The null hypothesis states that p<sub>0</sub> = 0.45.</hint>
            </part>
            <part>
                <response input="J" match="0.45" score="1">
                    <feedback>Correct.</feedback>
                </response>
                <response input="J" match="*">
                    <feedback>Incorrect. The assumption about the true population
                    proportion is the null hypothesis.</feedback>
                </response>
                    <hint>The assumption about the true population
                    proportion is the null hypothesis.</hint>
                    <hint>The assumption is that the true population
                        proportion is 0.45.</hint>
            </part>
        </question>
    </page>
   

</assessment>
